article.headline: Minnesota 63, Southeastern Louisiana 61
article.story: MINNEAPOLIS (AP) ---- Pressure practice possessions paid off Saturday for Minnesota. Spencer Tollackson tipped in a miss of a Lawrence McKenzie shot at the buzzer and the Gophers squeaked past Southeastern Louisiana 63-61 in the final non-conference game for each team. After Tavaris Nance tied the game with a tip with 7.4 seconds to play, McKenzie raced down the court and put up a short jumper against Terry Bryant. The shot bounced off the rim, but Tollackson outjumped fellow Gopher Dan Coleman to push the ball back into the net as the red light came on. "I didn't hesitate at all. I just threw it up there," said Tollackson, who led the Gophers with 21 points. "It's a credit to the coaches because we work on those situations every day in practice." McKenzie had 17 points and Coleman 13 for Minnesota (6-8), which hosts Purdue on Wednesday in its Big Ten opener. Daryl Cohen led the Lions with 16 points. Joseph Polite had 13 and Bryant 12 for Southeastern Louisiana (8-5), which lost for the first time in four games. The Lions welcome Sam Houston State in their Southland Conference opener Thursday. "These experiences will help us," said Lions coach Jim Yarbrough. "We were right where we wanted to be at the end, and we thought we'd go to overtime." McKenzie, who scored all his points in the second half, drove into traffic and his short jumper went off the glass and in with 57.7 seconds to play for a 59-58 lead. Bryant made one of two free throws to tie the game for Southeastern Louisiana, before Limar Wilson sank two with 36.1 seconds to play for a 61-59 Minnesota lead. "We're just trying to establish excellence or greatness through attitude," said interim coach Jim Molinari. "They stayed together. ... If we let up the least bit we're in real trouble." Trailing 29-24 early in the second half, Cohen hit three 3-pointers and Nance had a steal and dunk during a 15-2 run for the Lions, which won 69-66 at Penn State two weeks earlier. "We don't want to get ourselves in that kind of predicament, but this team is working hard and when you work hard I think things definitely pay off and good things happen," said McKenzie, who helped ignite Minnesota's offense. A steal and layup by Wilson and a layup in traffic by McKenzie got Minnesota within 46-45 with eight minutes to play. McKenzie sparked a 10-2 Minnesota run to go in front 51-48 with just under five minutes to play. He scored on a pair of lay-ups and a pair of free throws. The second half scoring was in stark contrast to the first half woes for each team. At one point Minnesota went more than eight minutes in the first half without a basket; the Lions almost seven. Minnesota shot 62.5 percent in the second half; Southeastern Louisiana 51.6 percent. After a non-conference season that ended with a record below .500 and a different coach, Tollackson hopes Minnesota can use this game as a springboard into conference play. "It's the second season for us, and we're really excited," he said. "I think guys showed each other tonight, and we showed a lot of people, that there is no quit in this team. We're definitely ready." The Gophers played without sophomore Brandon Smith, who was suspended indefinitely on Friday for breaking unspecified team rules. The forward started nine of the first 11 games, but saw just two minutes of action in the team's last two games.
